# Why Is Climate Change a Threat? A Comprehensive Analysis

Climate change has emerged as one of the most pressing global challenges of the 21st century. Its multifaceted impacts extend beyond environmental degradation to affect human health, economic stability, social structures, and global security. This report provides an in-depth, evidence-based analysis of why climate change constitutes a significant threat, drawing from a wide range of trusted and recent sources. The discussion integrates scientific consensus, environmental consequences, health impacts, socio-economic ramifications, and security concerns, presenting a holistic understanding of the threat posed by climate change.

---

## Scientific Consensus on Climate Change

There is an overwhelming scientific consensus that climate change is real, primarily anthropogenic (human-caused), and accelerating. Studies indicate that over 99% of recent scientific literature agrees that the climate is warming due to human activities, particularly the emission of greenhouse gases from fossil fuel combustion, deforestation, and land-use changes ([Cook et al., 2016](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate_change); [Powell, 2019](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate_change)). No reputable national or international scientific body disputes this view ([Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, 2021](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate_change)).

The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) 2021 Assessment Report states unequivocally that human activities are the dominant cause of observed warming since the mid-20th century. Despite some skepticism in public discourse, the scientific community’s consensus has only strengthened over time ([IPCC, 2021](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate_change)).

